an be used to strip sheath but there is still the possibility that you'll gouge the For any substantial amount of work with armored cable it's well worth your while to invest in a rotary cable splitter US Hack saws are tricky to use without cutting into the wire or the Three prong outlet testers are a quick check for properly wired About Multimeters tell you more but are a lot more expensive and probably not worth it for most A simple voltage sensor which can detect potential through an insulated wire not supplying any devices is extremely helpful they cost about US at Radio You should have a voltage detector to check that the wires are dead before doing work on Neon bulb version are cheap and work If you get more serious a audible alarm type is good for tracing circuits without a Though I've been known to lock the drill on and hit breakers until the scream stops For running wires through existing walls you need fish Often two tapes are needed though sometimes a bent hanger or a length of thin chain will Fish tapes can be Electrical Lots of it Seriously a good and competent wiring job will need very little The tape is useful for wrapping dicy insulation in repair Another use is to wrap around the body of outlets and switches to cover the termination screws I don't do this but drywall contractors prefer it to prevent explosions when the drywall knife collides with a live outlet that has no cover plate Subject What is UL listing The UL stands for Underwriters Laboratory It used to be an Insurance Industry organization but now it is independent and non It tests electrical components and equipment for potential When something is UL listed that means that the UL has tested the device and it meets their requirements for safety ie fire or shock It doesn't necessarily mean that the device actually does what it's supposed to just that it probably won't kill The UL does not have power of law in the you are permitted to buy and install non UL listed However insurance policies sometimes have clauses in them that will limit their liability in case of a claim made in response to the failure of a non UL listed Furthermore in many situations the NEC will require that a wiring component used for a specific purpose is UL listed for that Indirectly this means that certain parts of your wiring must be UL listed before an inspector will approve it and or occupancy permits Subject What is CSA approval Every electrical device or component must be certified by the Canadian Standards Association before it can be sold in Implicit in this is that all wiring must be done with CSA approved They perform testing similar to the UL a bit more stringent except that CSA approval is required by Again like the UL if a fire was caused by non CSA approved equipment your insurance company may not have to pay the In Canada there is a branch organization of the UL called ULC UL of Canada ULC does not have power of law and seems to be more a liason group between the CSA and insurance Subject Are there any cheaper easier to read books on wiring USA The following three books were suggested by our readers Residential Wiring by Jeff Markell Craftsman Books Carlsbad CA for ISBN Practical Electrical Wiring Residential Farm and Industrial Based on the National Electrical Code ANSI NFPA Herbert Richter and Creighton Schwan McGraw Hill Book Wiring Simplified Richter and Schwan Park Publishing Try to make sure that the book is based on the latest NEC Which is currently Canada Knight authors and publishes a book called Electrical Code Simplified There appears to be a version published specific to each province and is very tied into the appropriate provincial It focuses on residential wiring and is indispensible for Canadian DIY' It is better to get this book than the CEC unless you do a lot of wiring or answer questions on the net It is updated each time the provincial codes This book is available at all DIY and hardware stores for less than C Subject Inspections how and what Why should I get my wiring inspected Most jurisdictions require that you obtain a permit and inspections of any wiring that is Amongst other more mundane bureaucratic reasons like insurance companies not liking to have to pay claims a permit and inspections provides some assurance that you your family your neighbors or subsequent owners of your home don't get killed or lose their homes one night due to a sloppy wiring Most jurisdictions have the power to order you to vacate your home or order you to tear out any wiring done without a California for instance is particularly nasty about If fire starts in your home and un inspected wiring is at fault insurance companies will often refuse to pay the damage In general the process goes like this you apply to your local inspections office or building department for a You should have a sketch or detailed drawing of what you plan on This is a good time to ask questions on any things you're not sure If you're doing major work they may impose special conditions on you require loading calculations and ask other At this point they will tell you which inspections you will If you're installing a main panel you will need to have the panel and service connections inspected before your power utility will provide a This is sometimes done by the local power authority rather than the usual After installing the boxes and wiring but before the insulation walls go up you will need a rough in After the walls are up and the wiring is complete you will need a final inspection Subject My house doesn't meet some of these rules and Do I have to upgrade In general there is no requirement to upgrade older dwellings though there are some exceptions ie smoke detectors in some cases However any new work must be done according to the latest electrical Also if you do major'' work you may be required to upgrade certain existing portions or all of your Check with your local electrical Subject A word on voltages One thing where things might get a bit confusing is the different numbers people bandy about for the voltage of a One person might talk about another or another These are all in fact exactly the same In North America the utility companies are required to supply a split phase volt feed to your This works out as two Additionally since there are resistive voltage drops in the house wiring it's not unreasonable to find has dropped to or has dropped to by the time the power reaches a wall Especially at the end of an extension cord or long circuit For a number of reasons some historical some simple personal orneryness different people choose call them by slightly different This FAQ has chosen to be consistent with calling them and except when actually saying what the measured voltage will Confusing A Just ignore One thing that might make this a little more understandable is that the nameplates on equipment ofen show the lower ie instead of What this implies is that the device is designed to operate properly when the voltage drops that is not the same as is the voltage between phases of a phase Y circuit that is from neutral to any is the voltage between phases of a phase Y circuit that's from hot to In keeping with versus strangeness motors intended to run on three phase are often labelled as Subject What does an electrical service look like There are logically four wires involved with supplying the main panel with Three of them will come from the utility pole and a fourth bare wire comes from The bare wire is connected to one or more long metal bars pounded into the ground or to a wire buried in the foundation or sometimes to the water supply pipe has to be metal continuous to where the main water pipe entering the Watch out for galvanic action conductivity breaks often between copper and iron pipe This is the grounding conductor It is there to make sure that the third prong on your outlets is connected to This wire normally carries no One of the other wires will be white or black with white or yellow stripes or sometimes simply black It is the neutral It is connected to the centre tap CEC center tap in the NEC of the distribution transformer supplying the It is connected to the grounding conductor in only one place often inside the panel The neutral and ground should not be connected anywhere Otherwise weird and or dangerous things may Furthermore there should only be one grounding system in a Some codes require more than one grounding These will be connected together or connected to the neutral at a common point still one grounding Adding additional grounding electrodes connected to other portions of the house wiring is unsafe and contrary to If you add a subpanel the ground and neutral are usually brought as separate conductors from the main panel and are not connected together in the subpanel ie still only one neutral ground connection However in some situations certain categories of separate buildings you actually do have to provide a second grounding electrode consult your The other two wires will usually be black and are the hot They are attached to the distribution transformer as The two black wires are degrees out of phase with each This means if you connect something to both hot wires the voltage will be If you connect something to the white and either of the two blacks you will get Some panels seem to only have three wires coming into This is either because the neutral and ground are connected together at a different point eg the meter or pole and one wire is doing dual duty as both neutral and ground or in some rare occasions the service has only one hot wire only service Subject What is a circuit Inside the panel connections are made to the incoming These connections are then used to supply power to selected portions of the There are three different combinations one hot one neutral and ground two hots no neutral and ground two hots neutral and ground circuit neutral and or two circuits with a common is used for most circuits supplying receptacles and lighting within your is usually used for supplying power to major appliances such as stoves and dryers they often have need for both and or for bringing several circuits from the panel box to a distribution is usually for special motor circuits electric heaters or air Note In the US the NEC frequently permits a circuit similar to be used for stoves and dryers namely that there are two hot wires and a wire that does dual duty as neutral and ground and is connected to the frame as well as providing the neutral for purposes three prong plugs instead of four only for stoves dryers connected to the main When connected to most sub panels prong plugs and receptacles are required In our not so humble opinion this is crazy but the NFPA claims that this practice was re evaluated for the NEC and found to be Check your local codes or inquire as to local practice there are restrictions on when this is is usually wired with three conductor wire black for hot white for neutral and bare for and have one hot wire coloured red the other black a bare wire for grounding and in a white wire for You will sometimes see wired with just a black white and ground Since the white is hot in this case both the NEC and CEC requires that the white wire be permanently marked at the ends to indicate that it is a live Usually done with paint nail polish or sometimes electrical Each circuit is attached to the main wires coming into the panel through a circuit breaker or There are in a few locales circuits that look like or except that they have two bare ground Some places require this for hot tubs and the like one ground is frame ground the other attaches to the motor This may or may not be an alternative to GFCI Subject grounding versus grounded versus neutral According to the terminology in the CEC and NEC the grounding conductor is for the safety ground the green or bare The word neutral is reserved for the white when you have a circuit with more than one hot Since the white wire is connected to neutral and the grounding conductor inside the panel the proper term is grounded conductor However the potential confusion between grounded conductor and grounding conductor can lead to potentially lethal mistakes you should never use the bare wire as a grounded conductor or white wire as the grounding conductor even though they are connected together in the But not in subpanels subpanels are fed neutral and ground separately from the main In the trade and in common usage the word neutral is used for grounded conductor This FAQ uses neutral simply to avoid potential We recommend that you use neutral Thus the white wire is always except in some light switch applications Not Subject What does a fuse or breaker do What are the differences Fuses and circuit breakers are designed to interrupt the power to a circuit when the current flow exceeds safe For example if your toaster shorts out a fuse or breaker should trip protecting the wiring in the walls from As such fuses and breakers are primarily intended to protect the wiring UL or CSA approval supposedly indicates that the equipment itself won't cause a Fuses contain a narrow strip of metal which is designed to melt safely when the current exceeds the rated value thereby interrupting the power to the Fuses trip relatively Which can sometimes be a problem with motors which have large startup current For motor circuits you can use a time delay fuse one brand is fusetron which will avoid tripping on momentary A fusetron looks like a spring loaded A fuse can only trip once then it must be Breakers are fairly complicated mechanical They usually consist of one spring loaded contact which is latched into position against another When the current flow through the device exceeds the rated value a bimetallic strip heats up and By bending it trips the latch and the spring pulls the contacts Circuit breakers behave similarly to fusetrons that is they tend to take longer to trip at moderate overloads than ordinary With high overloads they trip Breakers can be reset a finite number of times each time they trip or are thrown when the circuit is in use some arcing takes place which damages the Thus breakers should not be used in place of switches unless they are specially listed for the Neither fuses nor breakers limit the current per A dead short on a circuit can cause hundreds or sometimes even thousands of amperes to flow for a short period of time which can often cause severe Subject Breakers Can't I use fuses Statistics show that fuse panels have a significantly higher risk of causing a fire than breaker This is usually due to the fuse being loosely screwed in or the contacts corroding and heating up over time or the wrong size fuse being installed or the proverbial replace the fuse with a penny Since breakers are more permanently installed and have better connection mechanisms the risk of fire is considerably Fuses are prone to explode under extremely high When a fuse explodes the metallic vapor cloud becomes a conducting Result from complete meltdown of the electrical panel melted service wiring through fires in the electrical distribution transformer and having your house burn Breakers don't do Many jurisdictions particularly in Canada no longer permit fuse panels in new The NEC does permit new fuse panels in some rare circumstances requiring the special inserts to key the fuseholder to specific size fuses Some devices notably certain large air conditioners require fuse protection in addition to the breaker at the The fuse is there to protect the motor windings from Check the labeling on the This is usually only on large permanently installed The installation instructions will tell you if you need Subject What size wire should I use For a amp circuit use gauge For a amp circuit you can use gauge wire in most locales For a long run though you should use the next larger size wire to avoid voltage gauge is only slightly more expensive than gauge though it's stiffer and harder to work Here's a quick table for normal Go up a size for more than foot runs when the cable is in conduit or ganged with other wires in a place where they can't dissipate heat easily Gauge Amps We don't list bigger sizes because it starts getting very dependent on the application and precise wire Subject Where do these numbers come from There are two considerations voltage drop and heat The smaller the wire is the higher the resistance When the resistance is higher the wire heats up more and there is more voltage drop in the The former is why you need higher temperature insulation and or bigger wires for use in conduit the latter is why you should use larger wire for long Neither effect is very significant over very short There are some very specific exceptions where use of smaller wire is The obvious one is the line cord on most Don't try this unless you're certain that your use fits one of those exceptions you can never go wrong by using larger Subject What does mean This is used to describe the size and quantity of conductors in a The first number specifies the The second the number of current carrying conductors in the wire but remember there's usually an extra ground means gauge two insulated current carrying wires plus bare wire usually has a black white and bare ground Sometimes the white is red instead for circuits without In the latter case the sheath is usually red wire usually has a black red white and bare ground Usually carrying with Subject What is a wirenut marrette marr connector How are they used A wire nut is a cone shaped threaded plastic thingummy that's used to connect wires Marrette or Marr connector are trade You'll usually use a lot of them in DIY In essence you strip the end of the wires about an inch twist them together then twist the wirenut Though some wirenuts advertise that you don't need to twist the wire do it anyways it's more mechanically and electrically There are many different sizes of wire You should check that the wire nut you're using is the correct size for the quantity and sizes of wire you're connecting Don't just gimble the wires together with a pair of pliers or your Use a pair of blunt nose linesman pliers and carefully twist the wires tightly and Sometimes it's a good idea to trim the resulting end to make sure it goes in the wirenut Some people wrap the open end of the wirenut with electrical This is probably not a good idea the inspector may tear it off during an It's usually done because a bit of bare wire is exposed outside the wire nut instead of taping it the connection should be Subject What is a GFI GFCI A GFCI is a ground fault circuit interrupter'' It measures the current current flowing through the hot wire and the neutral If they differ by more than a few milliamps the presumption is that current is leaking to ground via some other This may be because of a short circuit to the chassis of an appliance or to the ground lead or through a Any of these situations is hazardous so the GFCI trips breaking the GFCIs do not protect against all kinds of electric If for example you simultaneously touched the hot and neutral leads of a circuit and no part of you was grounded a GFCI wouldn't All of the current that passed from the hot lead into you would return via the neutral lead keeping the GFCI The two pairs of connections on a GFCI outlet are not One is labeled LOAD the other The incoming power feed must be connected to the LINE side or the outlet will not be The LOAD side can be used to protect all devices downstream from Thus a whole string of outlets can be covered by a single GFCI Subject Where should GFCIs be used The NEC mandates GFCIs for or single phase outlets in bathrooms kitchens within ' of the sink garages unfinished basements or crawl spaces outdoors near a pool or just about anywhere else where you're likely to encounter water or There are exceptions for inaccessible outlets those dedicated to appliances occupying fixed space'' typically refrigerators and freezers and for sump pumps and laundry The CEC does not mandate as many In particular there is no requirement to protect kitchen outlets or most garage or basement Basement outlets must be protected if you have a dirt floor garage outlets if they're near the door to Bathrooms and most exterior outlets must have Even if you are not required to have GFCI protection you may want to consider installing it Unless you need a GFCI breaker see below the cost is In the GFCI outlets can cost as little as US Costs are a bit higher in Canada C Evaluate your own risk Does your finished basement ever get wet Do you have small children Do you use your garage outlets to power outdoor tools Does water or melted snow ever puddle inside your garage Subject Where shouldn't I use a GFCI GFCIs are generally not used on circuits that a don't pose a safety risk and b are used to power equipment that must run unattended for long periods of Refrigerators freezers and sump pumps are good The rationale is that GFCIs are sometimes prone to nuisance Some people claim that the inductive delay in motor windings can cause a momentary current imbalance tripping the Note though that most GFCI trips are real if you're getting a lot of trips for no apparent reason you'd be well advised to check your wiring before deciding that the GFCI is broken or Subject What is the difference between a GFCI outlet and a GFCI breaker For most situations you can use either a GFCI outlet as the first device on the circuit or you can install a breaker with a built in The former is generally preferred since GFCI breakers are quite For example an ordinary GE breaker costs US the GFCI model costs US There is one major exception if you need to protect a multi wire branch circuit'' two or more circuits sharing a common neutral wire such as a Canadian style kitchen circuit you'll need a multi pole GFCI Unfortunately these are expensive the cost can range into the hundreds of dollars depending on what brand of panel box you But if you must protect such a circuit say for a pool heater you have no One more caveat GFCI outlets are You may want to use an oversize box when installing On second thought use large actually deep boxes You'll thank yourself for Incidentally if you're installing a GFCI to ensure that one specific outlet is protected such as a bathroom you don't really have to go to all of the trouble to find the first outlet in the circuit you could simply find the first outlet in the bathroom and not GFCI anything upstream of But protecting the whole circuit is When you install a GFCI it's a good idea to use the little ground fault protected stickers that come with it and mark the outlets downstream of the You can figure out which outlets are downstream simply by tripping the GFCI with the test button and see which outlets are Subject What's the purpose of the ground prong on an outlet then Apart from their use in electronics which we won't comment on and for certain fluorescent lights they won't turn on without a good ground connection they're intended to guard against insulation failures within the Generally the case of the appliance is connected to the ground If there's an insulation failure that shorts the hot lead to the case the ground lead conducts the electricity away safely and possibly trips the circuit breaker in the process If the case is not grounded and such a short occurs the case is live and if you touch it while you're grounded you'll get Of course if the circuit is GFCI protected it will be a very tiny zap which is why you can use GFCIs to replace ungrounded outlets both NEC and CEC There are some appliances that should never be In particular that applies to toasters and anything else with exposed Consider if you touch the heating electrode in a toaster and you're not grounded nothing will If you're slightly grounded you'll get a small shock the resistance will be too But if the case were grounded and you were holding it you'd be the perfect path to Subject Why is one prong wider than the other Polarization Nowadays many two prong devices have one prong wider than the This is so that the device could rely not guaranteed on one specific wire being neutral and the other This is particularly advantageous in light fixtures where the the shell should neutral safety or other devices which want to have an approximate ground reference ie some radios Most prong extension cords have wide prongs This requires that you wire your outlets and plugs the right way You want the wide prong to be neutral and the narrow one Most outlets have a darker metal for the hot screw and lighter coloured screw for the If not you can usually figure out which is which by which prong the terminating screw connects Subject What kind of outlets do I need in a kitchen The NEC requires at least two amp small appliance circuits'' for The CEC requires split duplex Outlets must be installed such that no point is more than NEC mm CEC from an Every counter wider than NEC or mm CEC must have at least one The circuit these outlets are on may not feed any outlets except in the kitchen pantry or dining Furthermore these circuits are in addition to any required for refrigerators stoves microwaves lighting Non dedicated outlets within ' of a sink must be protected by a GFCI NEC only Split duplex receptacles are fed with a The tab is broken on the hot side of the outlet and one hot goes to the upper outlet and the other hot goes to the lower The neutral connects to both outlets through one When carrying through to another outlet the neutral must be pigtailed such that removing the outlet or having the neutral connection fall off doesn't cause the neutral to disconnect from downstream Subject Where must outlets and switches be in bathrooms There must be at least one outlet in each bathroom adjacent to the sink in addition to any outlet that may be incorporated in the light All such outlets must be GFCI Subject What is Romex NM NMD What is BX When should I use each Romex is a brand name for a type of plastic insulated Sometimes called non metallic The formal name is This is suitable for use in dry protected areas ie inside stud walls on the sides of joists that are not subject to mechanical damage or excessive Most newer homes are wired almost exclusively with NM There are several different categories of NM BX cable technically known as armored cable or AC has a flexible aluminum or steel sheath over the conductors and is fairly resistant to TECK cable is AC with an additional external thermoplastic Protection for cable in concealed locations where NM or AC cable is run through studs joists or similar wooden members the outer surface of the cable must be kept at least CEC NEC from the edges of the wooden members or the cable should be protected from mechanical This latter protection can take the form of metal plates such as spare outlet box ends or Note inspector permitted practise in Canada suggests that armored cable or flexible conduit can be used as the mechanical protection but this is technically Additional protection recommendations these are rules in the Canadian codes they are reasonable answers to the vague references to exposed to mechanical damage in both the NEC and CEC NM cable should be protected against mechanical damage where it passes through floors or on the surface of walls in exposed locations under feet from the Ie use AC instead flexible conduit wooden guards Where cable is suspended as in connections to furnaces or water heaters the wire should be Canadian practise is usually to install a junction or outlet box on the wall and use a short length of AC cable or NM cable in flexible conduit to jump to the Stapling NM to a piece of lumber is also sometimes Where NM cable is run in close proximity to heating ducts or pipe heat transfer should be minimized by means of a air space or suitable insulation material a wad of fiberglass NM cable shall be supported within ' of every box or fitting and at intervals of no more than ' Holes in joists or studs 