to make your wiring The main problem with aluminum wiring is a phenomenon known as cold creep When aluminum wiring warms up it When it cools down it Unlike copper when aluminum goes through a number of warm cool cycles it loses a bit of tightness each To make the problem worse aluminum oxidises or corrodes when in contact with certain types of metal so the resistance of the connection goes Which causes it to heat up and corrode oxidize still Eventually the wire may start getting very hot melt the insulation or fixture it's attached to and possibly even cause a Since people usually encounter aluminum wiring when they move into a house built during the 's we will cover basic points of safe aluminum We suggest that if you're considering purchasing a home with aluminum wiring or have discovered it later that you hire a licensed electrician or inspector to check over the wiring for the following things Fixtures eg outlets and switches directly attached to aluminum wiring should be rated for The device will be stamped with Al Cu or CO ALR The latter supersedes the former but both are These fixtures are somewhat more expensive than the ordinary Wires should be properly connected at least way around the screw in a clockwise direction Connections should be While repeated tightening of the screws can make the problem worse during the inspection it would pay off to snug up each Note that aluminum wiring is still often used for the main service entrance It should be push in terminals are an extreme hazard with aluminum Any connections using push in terminals should be redone with the proper screw connections There should be no signs of overheating darkened connections melted insulation or baked Any such damage should be Connections between aluminum and copper wire need to be handled Current Canadian codes require that the wire nut used must be specially marked for connecting aluminum to The NEC requires that the wire be connected together using special crimp devices with an anti oxidant The tools and materials for the latter are quite expensive not practical to do it yourself unless you can rent the Any non rated receptacle can be connected to aluminum wiring by means of a short copper pigtail See Shows reasonable workmanship neat wiring properly stripped not nicked wire If when considering purchasing a home an inspection of the wiring shows no problems or only one or two we believe that you can consider the wiring If there are signs of problems in many places we suggest you look If the wrong receptacles are used you can replace them with the proper type or use pigtails having this professionally done can range from to per receptacle You can do this yourself Subject I'm buying a house What should I do It's generally a good idea to hire an inspector to look through the house for hidden Not just for wiring but plumbing and structural as If an inspection of the wiring shows no problems or only one or two minor ones we believe that you can consider the wiring safe after any minor problems are fixed If there are signs of problems in many places we suggest you look Here's some hints on what to look for Obvious non code wiring can include Zip cord wiring either concealed or nailed to walls Hot wiring on the identified neutral conductor without proper Ungrounded grounding outlets except when downstream of a GFCI Splices hanging in mid air other than proper knob and tube Switched neutrals Unsecured Romex swinging about like grapevines Certain wiring practises that are actually to code or were at one time sometimes reveal DIY wiring that may have hidden violations Switches that seem to control nothing abandoned perhaps not properly terminated wiring A wall switch that shuts off a group of lights that are separately controlled by other wall except when it's really convenient Switches and outlets in bizarre locations Great numbers of junction boxes without outlets or lamps Junction boxes with great numbers of wires going into them Wiring that passes through a closet instead of a wall or ceiling Backwrapped grounding wires Subject What is this weird stuff Old style wiring In the years since Edison invented electricity several different wiring styles have come and When you buy an older home you may encounter some of this This section describes the old methods and some of their The oldest wiring system you're likely to encounter is called knob and tube K T It is made up of individual conductors with a cloth The wires are run along side structural members eg joists or studs using ceramic stand offs knobs Wire is run through structural members using ceramic Connections were made by twisting the wire together soldering and wrapping with Since the hot and neutral were run separately the wiring tends to be rather A neutral often runs down the centre of each room with taps off to each The hot wire tended to run from one fixture to the In some cases K T isn't colour coded so the neutral is often the same colour as the hot You'll see K T in homes built as late as the ' Comments on K T the people installing K T were pretty paranoid about electricity so the workmanship tends to be pretty The wire insulation and insulators tend to stand up very Most K T I've seen for example is in quite good No Grounding is usually difficult to boxes are Receptacle replacement particularly with GFCI can be No bushing on boxes either so wiring changes need special attention to box Sometimes the neutral isn't balanced very well between separately hot circuits so it is sometimes possible to overload the neutral without exceeding the fusing on any Building code does not permit insulation in walls that contain K Connection to existing K T from new circuits can be Consult your Modern wiring practise requires considerably more outlets to be installed than K T systems Since K T tends to be in pretty decent condition it generally isn't necessary to replace it simply because it's K What you should watch out for is renovations that have interfered with it and be cautious about circuit In many cases it's perfectly reasonable to leave existing K T alone and add new fixtures on new circuits using modern After K T they invented multi conductor The first type you will see is roughly a cloth and varnish It looks much like the romex cable of the last decade or This stuff was used in the 's and ' Again no grounding It was installed much like modern Its major drawback is that this type of insulation We've seen whole systems where the insulation would fracture and fall off at a BX cable of the same vintage has similar This stuff is very fragile and becomes rather hazardous if the wires become This wiring should be left untouched as much as possible whenever an opportunity arises replace A simple receptacle or switch replacement can turn into a several hour long frustrating fight with electrical tape or heat shrink After this wiring technique the more modern romex was It's almost a asphalt impregnated Often a bit This stuff stands up reasonably well and doesn't present a hazard and is reasonably easy to work It does not need to be replaced it should be considered as safe as the modern stuff thermoplastic insulation Just don't abuse it too Subject Where do I buy stuff Try to find a proper electrical supply outlet near Their prices will often be considerably better than chain hardware stores or DIY centres have better quality materials have wider variety including the odd stuff and have people behind the counter that know what you're talking Cultivate friendly knowledgeable sales They'll give you much valuable Chris Lewis Phone Canada Psroff info Ferret list